WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.760
Patrick Rosal and Jean Valentine, we're going to read their poems and discuss each other's

00:06.760 --> 00:13.360
poems and we hope to have a very nice informal conversational experience in which the poets

00:13.360 --> 00:17.040
share their appreciations of each other's poetry.

00:17.040 --> 00:21.920
Patrick, we're lucky to have him as a member of our Poetry Committee here at Helix for

00:21.920 --> 00:24.280
our poetry programming.

00:24.280 --> 00:29.160
He's the author of three full-length poetry collections, most recently Bone Shepherds,

00:29.160 --> 00:35.520
named a notable book by the National Book Critics Circle and the Academy of American Poets.

00:35.520 --> 00:40.240
He's also won the Association of Asian American Studies Book Award, Global Filipino Literary

00:40.240 --> 00:45.560
Award, and the Asian American Writers Workshop Members' Choice Award.

00:45.560 --> 00:50.760
His poems and essays have been published in Grantland, Tin House, Harvard Review, Language

00:50.760 --> 00:54.880
for a New Century, Best American Poetry, and many others.

00:54.880 --> 01:00.120
He's a founding co-editor of some call it Ballin, a sports quarterly, and is a former

01:00.120 --> 01:01.960
Fulbright Fellow.

01:01.960 --> 01:07.720
He teaches on the faculty of Rutgers University, Camden's MFA program.

01:07.720 --> 01:13.840
And Jean Valentine, I think, is the author of a dozen books of poetry, the first being

01:13.840 --> 01:20.640
Dream Barker, which won the Young Young Poets Prize, up through her door on the mountain

01:20.640 --> 01:25.280
new and collected poems, which won the National Book Award for Poetry.

01:25.280 --> 01:30.840
And I think Break the Glass is the most recent book.

01:30.840 --> 01:36.480
She's a recipient of the 2009 Wallace Stevens Award from the Academy of American Poets.

01:36.480 --> 01:41.200
She's taught at Sarah Lawrence, NYU, and Columbia.

01:41.200 --> 01:48.960
So the format for this afternoon will be that Patrick's going to read some poems, and Jean's

01:48.960 --> 01:52.640
going to have a conversation with him about them.

01:52.640 --> 01:58.040
And then I think Jean is going to read her Lucy sequence, and Patrick is going to talk

01:58.040 --> 02:02.480
with her about his appreciation of that series of poems.

02:02.480 --> 02:04.640
Patrick will read a couple more poems.

02:04.640 --> 02:09.960
Jean will respond, and then I think Jean may finish with a couple of new poems.

02:09.960 --> 02:11.760
Is that still your plan?

02:11.760 --> 02:12.760
Super.

02:12.760 --> 02:16.800
And then we'll have time for the audience to comment.

02:16.800 --> 02:17.800
So we begin.

02:17.800 --> 02:18.800
Thank you very much.

02:18.800 --> 02:24.280
Thank you everybody for being here, too.

02:24.280 --> 02:30.160
I'm fighting what I hope is the tail end of a cold.

02:30.160 --> 02:40.400
I'm used to very energetic readings, but I'll muster whatever I can for today.

02:40.400 --> 02:46.360
A lot of the things that I've been interested in lately have been, I've always been interested

02:46.360 --> 02:52.760
in my family history, but more and more I've been trying to place that in terms of a global

02:52.760 --> 02:54.600
history.

02:54.600 --> 02:56.040
My parents are from the Philippines.

02:56.040 --> 03:02.120
This poem is called, The Lendre Undone.

03:02.120 --> 03:06.320
And so we've all been told to shut up.

03:06.320 --> 03:12.240
Don't talk, they say, too fast, too loud, or for too long.

03:12.240 --> 03:16.840
Don't take too much time trying to tell the truth.

03:16.840 --> 03:24.880
But this is my work, to break out among strangers into laughter.

03:24.880 --> 03:30.960
How I've watched small children, for example, fill with the lucky gust a poem can ride into

03:30.960 --> 03:35.440
the mere stillness of a room and dance.

03:35.440 --> 03:42.460
For that, I am always, as now, grateful.

03:42.460 --> 03:48.600
My father tells me in his seminary days, during the Japanese occupation, most of the priests

03:48.600 --> 03:51.520
who ran that school were German.

03:51.520 --> 03:56.560
The boys then were to speak only in Latin and would surely be slapped three Sundays

03:56.560 --> 04:01.600
back if heard speaking in the language of my father's country, which is a beautiful

04:01.600 --> 04:05.120
country and a beautiful language.

04:05.120 --> 04:14.840
And which has a curious word for being so suddenly seized by affection, you clench every muscle

04:14.840 --> 04:20.680
from your eyelids to your toes, for wanting to hold a loved one tight, squeeze one, and

04:20.680 --> 04:28.840
kiss one so deep you place yourself and your beloved on the brink of physical harm.

04:28.840 --> 04:32.360
There's no word for this in English.

04:32.360 --> 04:38.200
No word for those small provinces of silence or for the kind of love that will trouble

04:38.200 --> 04:41.480
that silence into music.

04:41.480 --> 04:50.760
My work is trying to find the very word rippling in my body, which is a woman's body, my mother's,

04:50.760 --> 04:57.160
and a man's body, my father's, and nowhere to be found in the languages that have conquered

04:57.160 --> 04:59.720
the land of my ancestors.

04:59.720 --> 05:05.360
In the outskirts of every empire, there are man-made lakes large enough to receive with

05:05.360 --> 05:09.880
ease, 100 villages worth of bones tossed into them.

05:09.880 --> 05:10.960
This is a fact.

05:10.960 --> 05:15.920
There are more than 7 million illocanos in the Philippines, maybe a million in diaspora.

05:15.920 --> 05:19.840
All of us at one time or another have been told to shut up.

05:19.840 --> 05:22.880
Don't talk too loud, too slow, or for too long.

05:22.880 --> 05:28.720
In Saudi Arabia, in Madrid, in Tokyo, in Milan, on Bowery, near the foot of First Street.

05:28.720 --> 05:30.360
You've been told this.

05:30.360 --> 05:37.360
Some of us have been famous liars, Ferdinand, for example, who married another liar, Ymelda,

05:37.360 --> 05:42.880
and my grandfather, Capitano de Barrio, who clinged to kick the shit bare-fisted and

05:42.880 --> 05:48.640
single-handedly out of 14 ruffians in the small barangay of Santatomas.

05:48.640 --> 05:52.000
Actually, he kicked the shit out of five.

05:52.000 --> 05:53.720
Nine ran away.

05:53.720 --> 05:55.600
These are not lies.

05:55.600 --> 05:57.200
This is the truth.

05:57.200 --> 05:58.520
I'm not wealthy.

05:58.520 --> 06:02.920
I can't buy space or time on billboards or websites.

06:02.920 --> 06:08.400
The name I inherit doesn't part columns in the city's daily journal.

06:08.400 --> 06:11.840
My family comes from a long line of farmers.

06:11.840 --> 06:15.800
My cousins scrubbed their chopping blocks with salt.

06:15.800 --> 06:22.480
They shushed the goats before they killed them.

06:22.480 --> 06:29.640
So Santatomas is essentially a barrio.

06:29.640 --> 06:35.160
And the barangay that my mom comes from is Santatomas.

06:35.160 --> 06:41.840
I was born and raised in New Jersey.

06:41.840 --> 06:46.360
I went to the Philippines for the first time when I was 14.

06:46.360 --> 06:50.560
But I didn't go back for almost 25 years.

06:50.560 --> 06:57.600
So this is a welcoming poem about how I got welcomed to the Philippines after 25 years.

06:57.600 --> 07:08.000
In the middle of my uncle's yard, a goat bounded the hooves wags its tongue.

07:08.000 --> 07:13.520
I've traveled 10,000 miles to be welcomed home by a town that knows me only by my middle

07:13.520 --> 07:18.760
name and photos sent by post more than 25 years ago.

07:18.760 --> 07:23.800
And there is an old man from the foothills of the barrio's far edge who has heard my

07:23.800 --> 07:27.400
uncle Charlie drag this small beast to the block.

07:27.400 --> 07:33.760
Heard the news by music, the bottles, the banging, the laughter inside the slaughter.

07:33.760 --> 07:40.040
The old man limps the half mile by foot up the long dirt road, unshod, a ratty tank top,

07:40.040 --> 07:46.640
a brand new Vegas cap, a cut black strip of inner tube draped around his neck.

07:46.640 --> 07:55.680
And in front of him, he's rolling the whole way, a common jug on its side, emptied of

07:55.680 --> 08:02.360
its vinegar, dusty, immense, to his hip in height and three times the old man's girth.

08:02.360 --> 08:08.080
My uncle is strumming the guts out of his ukulele when the old man arrives and sets the

08:08.080 --> 08:14.880
huge jug upright, pulls the bike tube off his nape and stretches it across the jar's massive

08:14.880 --> 08:21.440
ceramic yawn, holding the rubber strip in place with one big muddy toe and on the downbeat

08:21.440 --> 08:27.560
of the first measure of the second chorus, he joins my uncle in the kind of mooing these

08:27.560 --> 08:34.120
beloved geysers swear has several times tricked a field of blossoms into blue.

08:34.120 --> 08:40.520
The old man plucking from the makeshift base, not so much a moan, but a pulse that ranges

08:40.520 --> 08:47.480
a full octave into each man's chest, the sinews of the old timer's arm straining, the

08:47.480 --> 08:54.360
long muscle of his back top, his quadricep, his calves, his black foot pumping blood into

08:54.360 --> 09:02.280
his whole awful body, his maw flashing every one of his seven good teeth to have him.

09:02.280 --> 09:14.400
And if a man become part of a giant, the song of a giant, each one of us laughing like a

09:14.400 --> 09:21.480
giant, if each one of us fulfill the exact measure of a man, and if the goat at the same

09:21.480 --> 09:28.080
time is singing as it's dying among men who are singing and dying, the youngest cousin

09:28.080 --> 09:35.680
among us butcher slaughtering elbow deep in the animals belly does not sing.

09:35.680 --> 09:44.560
The carcass bloodlet now also silent as if it's stillness were a source of music too,

09:44.560 --> 09:52.680
the way in death one becomes all the sounds one cannot make, the sum total of everything

09:52.680 --> 10:01.480
the living cannot say, sometimes we have to sing just to figure out what we cannot say.

10:01.480 --> 10:02.480
Sure.

10:02.480 --> 10:11.480
Let us know how she feels about your problems.

10:11.480 --> 10:14.480
I love your problems.

10:14.480 --> 10:16.480
Thanks, Jean.

10:16.480 --> 10:19.520
And it's great to sit here beside you and hear them.

10:19.520 --> 10:25.320
Usually I'm over there hearing them and it's so nice to be near you.

10:25.320 --> 10:34.040
And I was thinking reading them the weeks coming up to now when we would be here.

10:34.040 --> 10:43.760
But I can't really, having her to read, I can't read these without hearing your voice.

10:43.760 --> 10:47.160
And it's so, it's such a gift.

10:47.160 --> 10:55.560
Even if I don't have it really in you being in the room, but the voice is so, as you can

10:55.560 --> 11:04.480
hear, the voice is so present in everything that writes and it's so important.

11:04.480 --> 11:12.120
And one thing I want to ask you is, I've probably been asked this before, but when you're writing,

11:12.120 --> 11:15.400
do you talk it while you're writing it?

11:15.400 --> 11:28.760
Yeah, I think that there's a sort of, you can call it a collaboration between my voice

11:28.760 --> 11:31.760
out loud and my interior voice.

11:31.760 --> 11:38.320
And so I don't know that I necessarily read it while I'm writing it down or composing,

11:38.320 --> 11:43.760
but I certainly, sometimes I will say something and I'll stop to record it.

11:43.760 --> 11:45.160
And then I'll read it again.

11:45.160 --> 11:54.160
So it becomes, it's like kind of transubstantiation between sound and ink, right?

11:54.160 --> 11:57.600
And it goes back and forth between those two substances.

11:57.600 --> 12:03.000
I think that's more what my process is like, but the out loud part feels very important

12:03.000 --> 12:04.000
to me.

12:04.000 --> 12:05.880
It's important to you too though, isn't it?

12:05.880 --> 12:06.880
Yeah.

12:06.880 --> 12:07.880
Yeah.

12:07.880 --> 12:18.560
It's important to every poet, but I hear, what you've said is perfect for me too, I think,

12:18.560 --> 12:21.680
but not the way I read, as you know.

12:21.680 --> 12:27.800
But I hear the voice inside, and then I put it down.

12:27.800 --> 12:35.320
But I wondered if you actually talked to yourself like Hamlet or somebody.

12:35.320 --> 12:39.480
Well, I love hearing you read.

12:39.480 --> 12:41.720
It's wonderful.

12:41.720 --> 12:45.080
It's beautiful.

12:45.080 --> 12:57.560
And I loved that you have this verse, I guess it is, by Neruda in the front of your book.

12:57.560 --> 13:00.880
You feel like reading that to the folks?

13:00.880 --> 13:01.880
I could do it.

13:01.880 --> 13:02.880
Yeah.

13:02.880 --> 13:10.400
I'd like you've had a chance to read that on, but it's wonderful to hear that voice too.

13:10.400 --> 13:14.560
So it's slipping for me now.

13:14.560 --> 13:18.520
My mind is, I'm drawing a blank.

13:18.520 --> 13:20.920
Anyway, I'll read the verse.

13:20.920 --> 13:22.200
It's from Heights of Machu Picchu.

13:22.200 --> 13:25.400
I can't remember which section it is though.

13:25.400 --> 13:28.640
Show me your blood and your furrows.

13:28.640 --> 13:34.480
Show me I was punished here because the jewel didn't shine or the earth didn't surrender

13:34.480 --> 13:37.680
it stone or grain on time.

13:37.680 --> 13:43.440
Point out to me the rock you fell upon and the wood on which they crucified you.

13:43.440 --> 13:49.680
Strike for me into fire the old flint, the ancient lanterns, the whips lashed upon those

13:49.680 --> 13:52.480
wounds throughout centuries.

13:52.480 --> 13:55.200
Show me blood-bright hatchets.

13:55.200 --> 14:00.480
I come to speak through your dead mouth.

14:00.480 --> 14:05.520
Thank you.

14:05.520 --> 14:11.760
I love having that in the front of your book because I think it's what you're doing.

14:11.760 --> 14:15.400
Not always dead mouths, but through others' mouths.

14:15.400 --> 14:18.520
And I think that's really what poetry is doing.

14:18.520 --> 14:20.720
Do you hear us okay?

14:20.720 --> 14:22.520
Yeah?

14:22.520 --> 14:32.360
I think the great poet Mary Ponzo is among us, so I just want to be sure she's hearing

14:32.360 --> 14:33.360
this.

14:33.360 --> 14:45.200
I think I've never really, I don't think, met a poet who isn't trying to speak for others

14:45.200 --> 14:57.040
at least some of the time and for people who couldn't speak for themselves oftentimes

14:57.040 --> 14:59.720
or who you feel that about.

14:59.720 --> 15:08.200
But when you read, I've seen you, we work together at Drew University, so I've seen Patrick

15:08.200 --> 15:15.200
read on different occasions something formal like this or something where you're helping

15:15.200 --> 15:22.480
to get something going or to announce students' names who are going to read at that time

15:22.480 --> 15:23.480
or something like that.

15:23.480 --> 15:30.680
So I've seen you in different degrees of formality or not.

15:30.680 --> 15:46.120
I think you have such a gift of really using your body, I know you must hear this all the

15:46.120 --> 15:53.400
time, but really the whole body comes into Pat's poetry and not just the voice.

15:53.400 --> 16:02.240
So that's something like I suppose we might be used to a great actor doing, but it isn't

16:02.240 --> 16:09.680
every poet who can even aspire to that and it's a wonderful gift I think.

16:09.680 --> 16:14.240
Can I say something?

16:14.240 --> 16:18.000
Of course you can't.

16:18.000 --> 16:26.480
The Kwame Dawes says, he talks about the sound of a drum and that the striking of the drum,

16:26.480 --> 16:33.080
the moment that you strike it, the attack is like a consonant.

16:33.080 --> 16:39.560
And when the drum rings, those are like the vowels of language, so he likens language

16:39.560 --> 16:42.080
to making drums.

16:42.080 --> 16:45.080
My buddy Roger just told me this last night, I think it's brilliant.

16:45.080 --> 16:52.240
What I think also is fascinating about that too is that in terms of language, the consonants

16:52.240 --> 16:55.920
are mostly made here up in the mouth.

16:55.920 --> 17:05.080
So those become the percussion and the metronomic sounds in a line or in a poem and that ringing

17:05.080 --> 17:13.800
of the drum, boom, the vowels, they become the harmonics that come between percussiveness,

17:13.800 --> 17:18.920
but they also, they come literally from the body in order to sing them out loud.

17:18.920 --> 17:28.280
You can't say a vowel without, it comes from the body and so, you know, I wasn't trained

17:28.280 --> 17:34.000
as a singer and an actor, but I think that I've always felt very, I was a dancer, I was

17:34.000 --> 17:36.200
a street dancer when I was younger.

17:36.200 --> 17:39.720
I've always felt very connected to my body.

17:39.720 --> 17:48.560
So I think that you're reading something about my own practices and my own engagement with

17:48.560 --> 17:49.560
art.

17:49.560 --> 17:52.760
Coming from that, yeah.

17:52.760 --> 17:54.760
Yeah, thanks, that's fascinating.

17:54.760 --> 18:02.280
I never thought of that consonant vowel thing before, but you mentioned musical instruments

18:02.280 --> 18:10.440
and it's a mouth a lot in your poetry, of course, drums, we just had a wonderful one, that amazing

18:10.440 --> 18:12.440
barrel with the tire.

18:12.440 --> 18:16.160
God, I love that.

18:16.160 --> 18:22.120
And then guitars and, yeah, homemade things.

18:22.120 --> 18:24.120
Yeah.

18:24.120 --> 18:25.120
Piano.

18:25.120 --> 18:27.560
Piano is definitely piano.

18:27.560 --> 18:28.560
Yeah.

18:28.560 --> 18:29.640
Beautiful one.

18:29.640 --> 18:33.520
Maybe you'll read that to us later on.

18:33.520 --> 18:35.320
That's a big poem.

18:35.320 --> 18:45.960
You know, when I was young, I think the biggest reader I ever heard are the most impressive

18:45.960 --> 18:48.440
reader I ever heard was Dylan Thomas.

18:48.440 --> 18:49.440
Oh, wow, yeah.

18:49.440 --> 18:51.200
You ever hear recordings of him?

18:51.200 --> 18:52.200
I have, I have.

18:52.200 --> 18:53.200
Yeah.

18:53.200 --> 18:58.640
And I think although it's different, he came from a tradition, the Welsh tradition of

18:58.640 --> 19:07.720
singing and reading and he just took our heads off when he came over here, you know?

19:07.720 --> 19:09.560
I just, I never heard anything like it.

19:09.560 --> 19:13.520
I'm sure there was stuff like it, but I just never heard it.

19:13.520 --> 19:14.520
Yeah.

19:14.520 --> 19:20.200
And speaking of consonants, I mean, the way that he sort of was able to conjure sound

19:20.200 --> 19:22.560
in a poem is just unbelievable.

19:22.560 --> 19:25.440
He's a real model for me in that way.

19:25.440 --> 19:26.440
He's a real model.

19:26.440 --> 19:27.440
Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

19:27.440 --> 19:28.440
Yeah.

19:28.440 --> 19:29.440
Wow.

19:29.440 --> 19:39.560
There's so many different styles of reading, but I really love, I love sound so much.

19:39.560 --> 19:42.280
It feels like it's more than half of what goes on.

19:42.280 --> 19:48.320
Were there any readers throughout your career?

19:48.320 --> 19:49.320
Were there any readers?

19:49.320 --> 19:58.000
I think that it's sort of, it's easy to perhaps remember people who are dynamic.

19:58.000 --> 20:00.600
They're like readers and good readers.

20:00.600 --> 20:07.600
But were there readers who were more pulled back that you found not just their poems being

20:07.600 --> 20:12.600
sort of arresting, but the performance of their poems?

20:12.600 --> 20:14.600
Being arresting?

20:14.600 --> 20:20.480
Yeah, or being able to grab your attention by being not sort of bardic necessarily, but

20:20.480 --> 20:23.040
more interior in their performance.

20:23.040 --> 20:27.840
Oh, more interior and arresting in that way.

20:27.840 --> 20:28.840
Yeah.

20:28.840 --> 20:29.840
More.

20:29.840 --> 20:34.840
Yeah, I would think, well, let me just think for a minute.

20:34.840 --> 20:43.960
There was a couple of interesting things about Robert Lowell.

20:43.960 --> 20:46.240
I don't know if you've heard him on a tape or anything.

20:46.240 --> 20:48.880
I think he'd never heard any tapes of him read ever.

20:48.880 --> 20:53.240
Well, he was from New England, but he had gone into a southern accent somewhere along

20:53.240 --> 20:54.240
the way.

20:54.240 --> 20:56.920
It was important to him.

20:56.920 --> 21:02.440
So that was one surprise when you heard him read if you didn't know anything about him.

21:02.440 --> 21:06.120
You thought he came from Boston, which he did.

21:06.120 --> 21:14.120
But then he, at first, would we, and I didn't hear this, but he talked about it in interviews.

21:14.120 --> 21:17.000
I don't know if any of you ever heard him in life?

21:17.000 --> 21:19.000
You did, yeah.

21:19.000 --> 21:22.840
Oh, great evening at St. Mark's Church.

21:22.840 --> 21:25.040
Ginsburg was there.

21:25.040 --> 21:29.920
And Peter Orlowski was sort of giving him a hard time from the sidelines.

21:29.920 --> 21:33.160
And Ginsburg was very like a supplicant.

21:33.160 --> 21:37.600
It was surprising to see, because most of us were sort of younger, heard of hippie-ish

21:37.600 --> 21:40.120
group, sort of on the Ginsburg side of things.

21:40.120 --> 21:43.240
He got right down and he kind of kneeled in front of Lowell as he was reading.

21:43.240 --> 21:44.240
It was Ginsburg.

21:44.240 --> 21:46.240
It was quite a sight.

21:46.240 --> 21:47.240
That's wonderful.

21:47.240 --> 21:50.240
I think they became friends at the end.

21:50.240 --> 21:52.240
Yeah, that's beautiful.

21:52.240 --> 21:59.280
I heard that they went on a march to Washington together.

21:59.280 --> 22:03.600
And there was a reading, and of course Ginsburg is heard by everyone.

22:03.600 --> 22:06.520
And Lowell got up there, and there was a mic and everything.

22:06.520 --> 22:08.800
But people kept saying, we can't hear you.

22:08.800 --> 22:10.320
We can't hear you.

22:10.320 --> 22:13.600
And he said, well, I can't do anything.

22:13.600 --> 22:16.120
I could shout, but you still wouldn't hear me.

22:16.120 --> 22:18.640
It was a big, huge crowd of people, I guess.

22:18.640 --> 22:20.360
He just didn't have that Ginsburg.

22:20.360 --> 22:28.120
But the interesting thing that I was going to say is anecdotal anyway, that he would

22:28.120 --> 22:32.600
read quite formally as he wrote at the beginning.

22:32.600 --> 22:36.840
And I think quite resolved.

22:36.840 --> 22:39.440
But then he went out on a reading tour in California.

22:39.440 --> 22:43.240
He said, no, the country in those days.

22:43.240 --> 22:48.720
It was very different, politically and far geographically.

22:48.720 --> 23:02.040
And I think he sensed that nobody understood a word he was saying in this very formal,

23:02.040 --> 23:11.680
very kind of formal metrics as well as formal language.

23:11.680 --> 23:13.920
And it was before life studies.

23:13.920 --> 23:16.760
It was the more formal work before that.

23:16.760 --> 23:18.800
